 your payments and make sure you pay in time.</p>\n\n<h2>Pay in instalments</h2>\n\n<p>If you&rsquo;re paying in instalments, ask the person or business you owe the money to about the best way to pay. </p>\n\n<p>You may want to set up a standing order to pay the money directly from your bank account.</p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>If you’re late with your payments, you could be taken back to court and you may have to pay extra costs.</p>\n</div>\n\n<h2>Ask to change the payments</h2>\n\n<p>You can ask to change the amount you pay per week or per month.</p>\n\n<p>To do this, fill in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=486\" title=\"N245 application form\">N245 application form.</a></p>\n\n<p>Give details of your income and spending, and say how much you can realistically afford to pay.</p>\n\n<p>You may have to pay a £40 <a href=\"/court-fees-what-they-are/\" title=\"court fee\">court fee</a>.</p>\n\n<p>If your offer is rejected, the court will decide on the amount you have to pay.</p>\n\n<h2>If you&rsquo;re threatened with bailiffs</h2>\n\n<p>The person or business you owe money to may use bailiffs to collect the money.</p>\n\n<p>They&rsquo;ll have to apply to the court for a &lsquo;warrant&rsquo;, which will give the bailiff the right to visit your home or property.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll be given 7 days to pay before they visit.</p>\n\n<p>You may be able to stop the bailiff from visiting, by filling in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctsformfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=486\" title=\"application to vary an instalment order\">N245 application form.</a></p>\n\n<p>Say on the form how you&rsquo;ll repay the money - eg weekly or monthly payments.</p>\n\n<p>If your offer is accepted, the warrant will be stopped as long as you keep up with the payments.</p>\n\n<h2>If you have other judgments or debts</h2>\n\n<p>If you have another judgment against you, you can arrange to pay all your debts to the court in a single weekly or monthly payment.</p>\n\n<p>This will stop people taking action against you to get their money - eg by sending bailiffs to your home.</p>\n\n<p>You can only do this if your total debts are under £5,000.</p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll need to fill in the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://hmctscourtfinder.justice.gov.uk/HMCTS/GetForm.do?court_forms_id=651\" title=\"application for an administration order\">application for an administration order (N92).</a></p>\n\n<div class=\"application-notice help-notice\">\n<p>Contact the court if you can’t keep up with the payments.</p>\n</div>\n"},{"web_url":"https://www.gov.uk/county-court-judgments-ccj-for-debt/ccjs-and-your-credit-rating","slug":"ccjs-and-your-credit-rating","order":4,"title":"CCJs and your credit rating","body":"<p>If you get a county court judgment (CCJ) or a High Court judgment, it will stay on the Register of Judgments, Orders and Fines for 6 years. </p>\n\n<p>Banks and loan companies use this information to decide whether to give you credit or loans.</p>\n\n<h2>If you pay within a month</h2>\n\n<p>If you pay the full amount within a month you can get the judgment removed from the register.</p>\n\n<h2>If you pay after a month</h2>\n\n<p>If you pay after a month, you can get the record of the judgment marked as &lsquo;satisfied&rsquo; in the register.</p>\n\n<p>It will stay on the register for 6 years but people searching the register will see that you&rsquo;ve paid.</p>\n\n<p>Contact the court to say you&rsquo;ve paid - you&rsquo;ll need to send proof of payment, and pay a £15 court fee.</p>\n\n<h2>Search the register of judgments</h2>\n\n<p>You can search for details of any judgments against you on the <a rel=\"external\" href=\"http://www.trustonline.org.uk/search-yourself/\" title=\"register of judgments\">register of judgments.</a></p>\n\n<p>You&rsquo;ll have to pay a small fee - a simple search costs £4.</p>\n\n<p>If the information o